WorkItem.Description:
```
declare module "./fake/module" {
  export var foo;
}

import fakeModule = module("./fake/module")
var foo = fakeModule.foo;
```

This code works in 0.8.2 but not 0.8.3. In 0.8.3 the error is:
Incorrect reference: imported file: "./fake/module" cannot be resolved.

Just curious if breaking this was on purpose or a side affect of some other change.

In case you're wonder why I would want to do something like this, I use this type of code to autogenerate javascript code that typescript code references and all of it gets browserified. I use the declaration so temporary/autogenerated code isn't intermingled with source code.

Comments.Message:
+1
I use this to generate AMD modules referencing custom dojo loader plugins. For example:

```
declare module "./myPlugin!./url" {
    var text: string;
}
import a = module("./myPlugin!./url");
alert(a.text);

```

Not sure how to do this in 0.8.3 and had to roll back to 0.8.2 for now
